# Frontend Design Skill — Activation Guidelines

## When to Use This Skill

Read `~/.cursor/skills/frontend-design/SKILL.md` before writing any frontend code when the request involves:

### Always Activate
- Building any web component, page, or full application from scratch
- Creating React components, HTML/CSS layouts, Vue components
- Any request to "style", "beautify", "redesign", or "polish" an existing UI
- Landing pages, portfolios, dashboards, posters, marketing pages
- Requests where the visual output will be seen by end users

### Activate When Context Suggests UI Work
- User mentions a design aesthetic (minimal, dark mode, glassmorphism, brutalist, retro, etc.)
- User specifies a color scheme, font preference, or mood/tone
- User shows a screenshot or reference and asks to replicate or improve it
- User asks for a component that has visible output (cards, modals, navbars, forms, heroes, etc.)

### Do NOT Activate
- Pure backend/API code with no visual component
- CLI tools, scripts, or data processing
- Writing tests or configuration files
- Documentation with no UI output

## Core Principles to Apply (from the Skill)

**Before writing code:**
- Commit to a BOLD, specific aesthetic direction — do not default to generic
- Identify the tone: brutally minimal, maximalist, retro-futuristic, luxury, playful, editorial, etc.
- Ask: what is the ONE thing someone will remember about this interface?

**Typography:**
- Never use Inter, Roboto, Arial, or system fonts
- Choose distinctive display + refined body font pairings from Google Fonts

**Color:**
- Use CSS variables for consistency
- Commit to a dominant palette with sharp accents — avoid timid, evenly-distributed colors
- Never use purple gradients on white as a default

**Motion & Effects:**
- Prefer CSS-only animations for HTML output
- One well-orchestrated page load with staggered reveals beats scattered micro-interactions
- Add atmosphere: gradient meshes, noise textures, geometric patterns, grain overlays

**Layout:**
- Break the grid intentionally: asymmetry, overlaps, diagonal flow, generous negative space

## Relationship to UI UX Pro Max Skill

Use **both skills together** when building full product UIs:
1. **UI UX Pro Max** → generates the design system (style, color palette, typography, industry rules)
2. **Frontend Design** → executes the implementation with production-grade aesthetics and code quality

Use **Frontend Design alone** for one-off components or when no industry-specific design system is needed.
